USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is only comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest, repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, which he himself considered the stupidest.
When he finally debunked his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it through a copycat from Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the name of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward."
At the same time, he himself criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq suffering from civil war as “irresponsible and, in its aftermath, catastrophic.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy based on the recommendations of the field commanders was the only one that was possible and successful enough that there is no mention of Iraq in the news reports today.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, but he objectively left his successor a much more appreciative initial situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked by field commanders to increase the military contingent, especially the top commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, even despite the subordination custom, harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't think of anything better, so at least he fooled the general with 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he was able to make a promise of another 5,000, even though he had originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and to end the process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half-fold increase will produce the same results as the Iraq procedure.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honor the agreement.
The Afghan situation is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are respected.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces, accustomed every day to change the master according to how it suits them.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a shadowy village, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the lack of transparency in the relations that further complicate Pakistan’s and Iran’s influence.
Even building an “actionable state,” which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, doesn’t seem too realistic.
The timing of Obama’s strategy is striking with his voluntarism.
The situation in Afghanistan has only worsened over the past eight years and is now on the verge of an explosion.
Believing that the soldiers sent to war in order to "quickly return home" will cause the miracle done here, only the soul can truly romantic, untouched reality.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is a clear irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is declining.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the Hindu Kush foothills.
Another factor capable of radically affecting the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions on Iran do not take effect, the difficult question will arise before the United States whether to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will be necessary to respond to it at a time when, according to Obama, the United States will proceed to a successful withdrawal from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only downside for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left in the presidential election, and therefore enough time left for him to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
