Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran along two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short front limbs with sickle claws and claw claws.
If this species lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the Thursday issue of the journal Science write that Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship relationships, expansions, and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for triassic deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The findings confirm theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other experts on dinosaurs do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the assignment of pradinosaurs is usually controversial.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards split into the three most important lines of development: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyranosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and also birds, "long-nosed" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and protozoans.
Tawa hallae is the original terapod after the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, researchers found evidence of air sacs, which even the descendants of theropods have birds.
Thanks to air vacuums, breathing birds is more effective than mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation has probably formed a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists have concluded that the lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development split early on and spread from South America to all the continents that, as the supercontinent of Pangaea at that time, formed a unified mass of the earth.
She would also talk about the fact that the team found, together with Tawa hallae, the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
These three cannot come from one common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of heaviest dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His hypothesis could put together a distorted picture, because in South America there are preserved very many primitive fossils of dinosaurs, while on other continents they are rarely found.
As dinosaurs have shown that they evolved from a relatively rare by-line of reptiles to the dominant vertebrates on earth during the Earth’s Middle Ages, it still remains a puzzle.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, including the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species evolved, while relatives became extinct and the interface of the Triassic and the Jury.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses for explaining this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction that dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the reptiles did not.
