But unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, “the sensory and spatial structure of reality that one perceives in psychosis remains fundamentally preserved.”
Misguided thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real context.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why exactly our brains are doing such sweeps.
“Exceptional states can cause any person to lose their relationship to reality in the short term,” Fuchs says.
Not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists believe that the affected people have minimal damage to the brain.
We believe that at an early stage of development, neuronal maturation of the brain will be damaged, for example, by viral diseases of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
