Nighttime dreams also evaluate casten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucination of healthy people is not fundamentally different from the hallucination in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Therefore, Kasten advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The borderline between sleep and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our over-concentrated world, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and head of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic at Florence-Nightingale Hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also brings positive, creativity - a delusion is also the art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a peculiar form of altered consciousness to dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictitious dreams that the person concerned considers real and cannot even distinguish them from the waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis in full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, perhaps by a permanent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, Schmidt-Degenhard says.
Type of borderline state between sleep and hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to cope with a situation, there will be a change of worlds, but the real situation will be present in the imagination.
An intense form of support for the senses and the transference of the senses in some intolerable situation that allows people to move within an instant into the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (Exchange of heart) as a rescue action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery and subsequent heart transplant, his consciousness was released on a several-day journey, with his body lying motionless on the intensive care unit.
Claussen plunged into the world he created, visited foreign times and places: He becomes an old man trapped in a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
It lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces narcotic substances from blood.
On a motorbike, he is taken by the Greek to his homeland, surfed on a hospital bed in the Alps, and met by a Korean mobster.
It sinks completely into the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
Contrary to dreams, the memories of these mental journeys are still clear after years and in minor details.
Even brighter and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug addiction show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even in the waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
A reality that can also be enriching.
