75% of working mothers have work-related problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of a study 'Fertility and career of Spanish women', conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labor market because of motherhood.
The study emphasizes that at the beginning of the partnership life there are many differences in opinions on the number of children, whether they work or not, and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with their partner earlier, give birth to their first child and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, are postponing cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer descendants.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of their cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and therefore had to postpone the cohabitation of partners and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, albeit a minor influence on the time of starting a life with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of marriage is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49 years, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 vs. 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education marry and give birth to their first child even before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education do the opposite, preferring to get a stable job, before marriage and the birth of their first child,” says Delgado.
